{{POV check|date=January 2009}} {{Tone|date=January 2009}} {{main|Population decline|Sub-replacement fertility}}
'''Birth dearth''' is a [[neologism]] referring to falling [[fertility rate]]s. In the late 1980s, the term was used in the context of [[United States|American]] and [[Europe]]an society.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/12/books/be-fruitful-and-multiply.html "Be Fruitful and Multiply"], Jamar Jacoby, ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 12, 1987</ref> The use of the term has since been expanded to include many other [[industrialized nation]]s. It is often cited as a response to [[Human overpopulation|overpopulation]], but is not incompatible with it. The term was coined by [[Ben Wattenberg]] in his 1987 book by that same name. Countries and geographic regions that are currently experiencing falling population include Russia, Europe, Japan, and populations of people of these descents in other countries such as in the United States.
== Russia == [[Russia]] is often mentioned in articles concerning birth dearth because of its rapidly declining population, and the proposal by [[Vladimir Putin]] to offer women additional benefits for having more children. It is predicted that Russia's population will be an estimated 111 million in 2050, instead to 147 million in 2000 if current trends continue, according to the UN World Population Prospects report (2004 Revision, medium variant).
== Europe == {{Main|Aging of Europe}} [[Europe]] is one of the few major geographic regions in the World that is expected to ''decline'' in [[population]] in the coming years. Europe's population is forecast to decline by nearly 70 million people by 2050,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifs.du.edu/ifs/frm_GraphicalDisplay.aspx?ListNames=%22Population,%20History%20and%20Forecast%22&HistFor=True&GrpOp=1&Dim1=%22Europe%22&File=0 |publisher=International Futures |title=Population of Europe, History plus Forecast |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> as the [[total fertility rate]] has remained perpetually below the replacement rate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifs.du.edu/ifs/frm_GraphicalDisplay.aspx?ListNames=%22Total%20Fertility%20Rate,%20History%20plus%20Forecast%22&HistFor=True&GrpOp=1&Dim1=%22Europe%22&File=0 |publisher=International Futures |title=Total Fertility Rate of Europe, History plus Forecast |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> (Further information: [[Sub-replacement fertility]] and [[Population decline]])
