{{Galaxy cluster | name = HCG 87 | image = File:HCG 87.png | caption = Galaxy Group HCG 87 | credit = | type = Compact galaxy group | distance = [[1 E24 m|400 million]] | ra = {{RA|20|48|11.9s}}<ref name="ned">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for HCG 87 | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/ | accessdate=2006-10-19 }}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-19|50|35}}<ref name="ned" /> | z = 8874 km/[[second|s]]<ref name="ned" /> | constellation = [[Capricornus]] | member_no = ~5 | main_member = [[Spiral Galaxy HCG 87a|HCG 87a]] | names = None }}
'''HCG 87''' is a compact [[group of galaxies]] listed in the [[Hickson Compact Group]] Catalogue. This group is about [[1 E24 m|400 million]] [[light-year]]s away <ref>[http://heritage.stsci.edu/1999/31/hicktable.ps This redshift corresponds to a distance of 120Mpc or 400 million light years (using H<sub>0</sub> = 75km/s/Mpc and q<sub>0</sub> = 0.1). At the distance of the group, this corresponds to a group diameter of 52kpc, i.e., the group is approximately 170,000 light years across.]</ref> in the [[constellation]] [[Capricornus]]. The group distinguishes itself as one of the most compact groups of galaxies, hosting two [[Active galactic nucleus|active galactic nuclei]] and a starburst among its three members, all of which show signs of interaction.<ref>Noll, Keith. 07/1999. "Hubble Heritage observations of Hickson Compact Galaxy Group 87".</ref> This interaction, which astronomers have called visually, and scientifically, intriguing<ref>English, J. et al. 05/2000. "A Minuet of Galaxies: Hickson Compact Group 87 as Viewed by the Hubble Space Telescope". American Astronomical Society, 195th AAS Meeting, #136.04; Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society, Vol. 32, p.884.</ref> is being examined to understand the influence of active nuclei on star formation histories.
