{{about|the chemist|the poet|Rebecca Goss}}
{{Infobox scientist | name = Rebecca Jane Miriam Goss | other_names = R. J. M. Goss (in publications) | workplaces = {{Plainlist| * [[University of St. Andrews]] * [[University of Exeter]] * [[University of East Anglia]] * [[University of Cambridge]] }} | alma_mater = [[University of Durham]] | thesis_title = | doctoral_advisor = David O'Hagan | awards = {{Plainlist| * [[Royal Society]] Dorothy Hodgkin Fellowship (2003) * Royal Society of Chemistry [[Meldola Medal and Prize|Meldola Medal]] (2006) * [[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]] Chemistry Journal Award (2011) }} }}
'''Rebecca Jane Miriam Goss''' is a professor of organic chemistry at the [[University of St Andrews|University of St. Andrews]] who won the 2006 [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] [[Meldola Medal and Prize|Meldola Medal]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/ScienceAndTechnology/Awards/HarrisonMeldolaMemorialPrizes/PreviousWinners.asp|title=RSC Harrison-Meldola Prize Previous Winners|website=www.rsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref> She is known for combining synthetic biology and chemistry for medicinal purposes.
== Early life and education == Goss completed her undergraduate studies in Chemistry at the [[Durham University|University of Durham]] in 1997.<ref name=":1" /> Under the supervision of Prof. David O'Hagan, Goss completed her Ph.D. studying the biosynthesis of various natural products including the [[stereochemistry]] of enzymatic [[fluorination]] in [[Fluoroacetates|fluoroacetate]] biosynthesis.<ref name=":1" />
== Research == Goss specialises in the [[biosynthesis]] of natural products at the chemical and genetic level.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://rjmg.wp.st-andrews.ac.uk/rebecca-goss/|title=Rebecca Goss {{!}} The Goss Lab|website=rjmg.wp.st-andrews.ac.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref>
Goss joined the [[University of Cambridge]] in 2000 to study the chemistry and molecular biology of polyketide biosynthesis in the research group of Professors Jim Staunton (FRS) and Peter Leadlay (FRS). She held a one year teaching fellowship at the School of Chemistry, [[University of Nottingham]] between 2002 to 2003 before obtaining a lectureship at the School of Biological and Chemical Science, [[University of Exeter]] in 2003.<ref name=":1" /> Between 2005 and 2010 Goss held a lectureship at the [[University of East Anglia]] before being promoted to senior lecturer in 2010 and then reader in organic chemistry in 2012.<ref name=":1" /> Goss moved to the [[University of St Andrews|University of St. Andrews]] in 2012 to become a reader in biomolecular and organic chemistry. In 2018 she became the first woman to be appointed professor of organic chemistry in St Andrews' 600 year history.<ref name=":1" />
She was awarded the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] [[Meldola Medal and Prize|Meldola prize]] for her work to understand the interface of organic chemistry and molecular biology.<ref name=":0" /> In 2013 she was awarded the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] [[Natural Product Reports|Natural Product Report]] Emerging Researcher Lectureship for her pioneering approach to 'Genochemetics', which combines synthetic biology and chemistry for medicinal purposes. In 2014 she was awarded an [[European Research Council|ERC]] consolidator grant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risweb.st-andrews.ac.uk/portal/en/persons/rebecca-jane-miriam-goss(67793718-7888-4ff5-9d92-5e4f0b6d3d41)/projects.html|title=Rebecca Goss - Funded projects - University of St Andrews|website=risweb.st-andrews.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref>
Goss is on the advisory board for the peer-reviewed journals [[Chemical Communications]] and [[Natural Product Reports]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/journals-books-databases/about-journals/chemcomm/#boards-staff|title=Chemical Communications|last=Chemistry|first=Royal Society of|date=2015-05-22|website=www.rsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/journals-books-databases/about-journals/npr/#boards-staff|title=Natural Product Reports|last=Chemistry|first=Royal Society of|date=2015-05-22|website=www.rsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref>
== Awards ==
* 2013 [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] Natural Product Report Lectureship Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pubs.rsc.org/en/journals/articlecollectionlanding?themeid=9e4d47e8-9cea-4334-8eb1-3dff68600f1f|title=Natural Product Reports Emerging Investigator Lectureship winners Home|website=pubs.rsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref> * 2011 UK’s under 40 Organic Chemistry delegate for [[EuCheMS|EuCheM]]’s Young Investigators Workshop<ref name=":1" /> * 2011 [[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]] Chemistry Journal Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thieme.de/en/thieme-chemistry/thieme-chemistry-journals-award-previous-winners-107365%20.htm|title=Previous Winners - Thieme Chemistry - Georg Thieme Verlag|work=Thieme|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> * 2006 [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] - [[Meldola Medal and Prize|Meldola prize]]<ref name=":0" />
